        {
            "id": "intro_logical_operators",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Logical Operators",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Logical operators help us combine multiple conditions. They work with Boolean values (`True` and `False`) to create more complex comparisons."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "and_operator",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "The `and` Operator",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `and` operator returns `True` only when both conditions are `True`. If either condition is `False`, the result is `False`."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "So basically, `and` means everything has to be true. One `False` will break the chain."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "print(True and True)\nprint(True and False)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "True\nFalse"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "or_operator",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "The `or` Operator",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `or` operator returns `True` when at least one condition is `True`. It only returns `False` when both conditions are `False`."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "So basically, `or` means at least one thing has to be true. One `True` will make the whole thing true."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "print(True or True)\nprint(True or False)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "True\nTrue"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "not_operator",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "The `not` Operator",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The `not` operator flips the Boolean value. It turns `True` into `False` and `False` into `True`."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "print(not True)\nprint(not False)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "False\nTrue"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
